5d. Adding many polynomial powers to the model makes the model increasingly harder to interpret. Additionally, higher-order terms might make the model more complex without actually improving its fit. Lastly, there is also the risk of ‘overfitting’, in which your model becomes too highly responsive to the data, and maybe even begins to fit noise. When a model is too closely matched to the training data set, it will fail to generalize well when applied to other datasets.

923.904-773.412
## [1] 150.492

On average, people with 4 children under the age of 5 work 150.492 hours fewer than people with 3 children under the age of 5.

6c. We cannot tell whether there’s a statistically significant difference in hours worked between having 2 children and having 3 children under the age of 5 from this table. If we are assessing whether a categorical variable has a significant effect as a whole, we need to look at all the category coefficients rather than the individual coefficients. This is achieved through a “joint F test,” where you compare the predictive power of the model against a version where the categorical variable has been removed as a predictor.

Loading data

dengue <- read.csv("https://vincentarelbundock.github.io/Rdatasets/csv/DAAG/dengue.csv")
  1. Run an OLS regression using average humidity to predict whether dengue was observed in the area, and look at the results.

Language-specific instructions:

  • In both R and Python, save the model as m2. In R, use the msummary() function from the modelsummary package to display the results with the stars = TRUE option.

Running regression

m2 <- lm(NoYes ~ humid, data = dengue)

msummary(m2, stars=c('*' = .1, '**' = .05, '***' = .01),
    output= 'regression_table.html')
  1. Write two sentences, one interpreting the intercept and one interpreting the slope.

When humidity is zero, the likelihood of dengue in a given area decreases by 0.416 on average. A one unit increase in humidity is associated with a 0.05-unit increase in the likelihood of dengue in a given area.

  1. Get a set of summary statistics for the humidity variable and write a comment on how this can help you make sense of the intercept in the regression from step 2.

Language-specific instructions:

  • We didn’t cover easy summary statistics commands in the book. In R you can use summary() on the variable. In Stata try summarize and in Python, data['variablename'].describe().
summary(dengue$humid)
   Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max.    NA's 
 0.6714 10.0088 16.1433 16.7013 23.6184 30.2665       2

Humid ranges from 0.6714 to 30.2665, with a fairly normal distribution, given that the mean and median are about the same (16). Therefore, it makes sense that when humidity is zero, the likelihood of dengue is decreased by a significant factor (almost 50 % – 0.416), because humidity is very rarely zero. It is most often around 16.

  1. Our dependent variable is binary, and we’re getting predictions below zero, which we might not want. Rerun the regression from question 5 but as a logit model, and report the marginal effects of both slope coefficients.

  1. A long one: Now let’s say we’re directly interested in the relationship between temperature and humidity. Run an OLS regression of humidity on temperature. Calculate the residuals of that regression, and then make a plot that will let you evaluate whether there is likely heteroskedasticity in the model. Rerun the model with heteroskedasticity-robust standard errors. Show both models, and say whether you think there is heteroskedasticity

Language-specific instructions:

  • In both R and Python, save the model as m7, and m7b if you rerun with robust standard errors.

In R, use fiter(!is.na(dengue$humid)) on the data before running the model so the residuals line up properly. Use the msummary() function from the modelsummary package to display the results with the stars = TRUE option. Also, if you’re clever about msummary() usage, you can skip creating m7b. You can access residuals using resid(m7).

In Stata, you can access residuals using predict resid, r after running the model.

In Python, use dengue.loc[~pd.isna(dengue['humid'])] on the data before running the model so the residuals line up properly. You can access residuals using m7.resid.

filtered_dengue <- dengue|> filter(!is.na(dengue$humid))
m7 <- lm(temp ~ humid, data = filtered_dengue)
msummary(m7, stars=c('*' = .1, '**' = .05, '***' = .01), output='regression_table_4.html')
resids <- resid(m7)
library(ggplot2)

First method: see how OLS predictions compare to actual values of Y across X

print(ggplot(filtered_dengue, aes(humid, temp)) + 
  geom_point() + geom_smooth(method='lm'))
`geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

Second method: graph residuals explicitly across X

#create new empty df; add x (humid) and residuals into it
resid_data <- data.frame(filtered_dengue$humid, resids)

Both graphs illustrate heteroskedasticity, as seen in the fact that the error terms are correlated, and vary systematically depending on the value of X. At very low and high humidity levels, error is positive. At mid-range humidity levels, error is negative.

In Stata, you’ll need to create logged humidity in the data before running the regression. In R and Python you can do it inside of the regression formula, using np.log() from numpy in Python.

m8 <- lm(temp ~ log(humid), data = filtered_dengue)
msummary(m8, vcov='robust', stars=c('*' = .1, '**' = .05, '***' = .01), output='regression_table_6.html')

For every 0.1-unit increase in log(humidity), humidity increases by 10%. Therefore, for a 0.1-unit increase in log(humidity), temperature changes by 0.1*13.636=1.3636 units.
